Thank you for subscribingWe have more newsletters Show me See our privacy notice Invalid Email ON January 8, 1887, members of the Heaton Chapel and District Liberal Club walked in procession from their old premises to a brand new purpose-built club. 
In addition to housing gentlemen of a Liberal persuasion the new building was to be the setting for many glittering social events held in the "Reform Hall", the upper hall of what is now known as Heaton Chapel Reform Club, even though it is in Heaton Moor. 
Recently the club, pictured right, announced that it is seeking planning permission to build flats at the rear to raise the money to keep the rest of the building going. 
So this is an appropriate time to look at its history, with thanks to Dr John Langrish who chronicled at the time of its centenary. 
The land purchase was not completed until July 1886, yet the building was occupied the following January, putting many of today's building projects to shame. 
Following an architectural competition, the club was designed by Alfred Darbyshire, who was also responsible for Heaton Moor Congregational Church. 
Members of that time must have been ace fund-raisers. 
All remaining liabilities were paid off in 1890 with a four-day Italian bazaar which raised £1,200, an amazing amount of money in those days. 
The rear portion of the building was added in 1906 with a grand bazaar the following year raising nearly £1,600. 
Letting of rooms was always the most profitable source of income for the club, although this started to decline in the 1950s and 1960s, due to increased competition and failure to modernise. 
The character and efficiency of the club has always been affected by the steward and his "wife to assist". 
The terms of appointment of a Mr and Mrs Hawes have survived from 1906 when they were rewarded with the magnificent salary of 35 shillings per week and were required to keep the club open from 9am to 11.30pm every day apart from Christmas Day, Good Friday and Sundays. 
The Reform Club was for men only during the whole of its first century and in the 1960s received the Guardian newspaper's "Burning Bra" award for its attitude to women. 
But women became full members in 1994, were elected to the committee the following year and in 2000 the annual doubles snooker competition was won by a husband-and-wife team. 
TWENTY YEARS AGO Marjorie Arrowsmith, 72, got a big surprise when she entered a disco dancing competition and won. 
Marjorie jumped onto the crowded dance floor at Cheadle Liberal Club and showed the youngsters how it should be done. 
Marjorie, from Cheadle Hulme, said: "When the judges came over and told me I'd won, I said 'I must be the oldest here', and he said, 'But you dance the best!'" A Stockport postman was chosen to be the picture on a jigsaw which would be sold in 39 countries worldwide. 
David Whitelegg was depicted on the children's jigsaw opening a post box for evening collection. 
David, from Cheadle Heath, was picked to represent the postal service as part of James Galt Company's series of 'People Who Work For Us' jigsaws. 
THIRTY YEARS AGO Around 3,000 residents in Cheadle Hulme were woken up in the early hours of the morning when a mystery gas leak caused an explosion scare. 
Police went round at midnight giving loudspeaker instructions to turn off gas supplies after gas pressure in the area had suddenly altered while workmen were testing the mains. 
A young family were being forced out of their home by a colony of mice. 
For the past year Peter Beedell, father of five young children, had been complaining to the local authority about the infestation in the Heaward Street property. 
He said: "The mice have won as far as I am concerned and they can have the house all to themselves." 
FORTY YEARS AGO A blanket of fog blacked out Stockport reducing visibility to almost nil and bringing most bus services to a standstill and leaving workers crawling home from the town centre in their cars. 
Under the cover of fog, several smash-and-grab raiders struck and police and health workers had to be issued with smog masks. 
The town's health officer warned everyone to wear smog masks in bad weather, or at least cover their faces with a handkerchief. 
A Disley man who won £20,000 on the pools at the weekend was made even happier several days later when he saw the Queen in Harrods. 
Arthur Pownall, 51, was out shopping in the London store following his big win when he turned to the shopper stood next to him and realised it was the Queen, which he said made his wife happier than the pools win did. 
Arthur said of his winnings: "I'd like to buy a little cabin cruiser. The money will also help buy my daughter a house." 
Published December 4, 2002 Most Read Most Recent Most Read Most Recent
